{"title_page": "Rockland County, New York", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Rockland, New York}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2011}}\n{{Infobox U.S. county\n| county             = Rockland County\n| state              = New York\n| type               = [[List of counties in New York|County]]\n| ex image           = Hook Mountain Nov2015.jpg\n| ex image cap       = View of the [[Hudson River]] looking southward from [[Hook Mountain State Park]].\n| ex image size      = 250px\n| seal               = Seal of Rockland County, New York.png\n| flag               = Flag of Rockland County, New York.jpg\n| founded            = 1798\n| leader type        = County Executive\n| leader_name        = Ed Day ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]])\n| seat wl            = New City\n| largest city       = New City\n| city type          = CDP\n| area_total_sq_mi   = 199.34\n| area_land_sq_mi    = 173.55\n| area_water_sq_mi   = 25.79\n| area percentage    = 13\n| census estimate yr = 2019\n| pop                = 325789<ref name=QF/>\n| density_sq_mi      = 1,895\n| web                = www.rocklandgov.com\n| district           = 17th\n| time zone          = Eastern\n| area codes         = 845\n}}\n{{maplink|frame=yes|zoom=8|id=Q111098|type=shape|text=Interactive map of Rockland County, New York}}\n'''Rockland County''' is the southernmost [[U.S. county|county]] on the west side of the [[Hudson River]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[New York (state)|New York]], part of the [[New York City]] [[New York metropolitan area|Metropolitan Statistical Area]]. The county's population, as of the [[2010 United States Census]], was 311,687, increasing to a 2019 Census estimate of 325,789,<ref name=QF>{{cite web|title=QuickFacts Rockland County, New York|url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/rocklandcountynewyork/PST045216|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=March 31, 2018}}</ref> making it the third-most densely populated county outside New York City within New York State (after [[Nassau County, New York|Nassau]] and neighboring [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester]] counties, respectively). The [[county seat]] is [[New City, New York|New City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx|accessdate=7 June 2011|title=Find a County|publisher=National Association of Counties}}</ref> Rockland County is a suburb of [[New York City]] that borders the boroughs about 9 miles northwest of the city at their closest points, and is accessible via the [[New York State Thruway]], after 10 exits. The name derives from \"rocky land\", as the area has been aptly described.\n\nRockland County is the smallest county by area in New York State outside [[New York City]]. It comprises five towns and nineteen incorporated villages, with numerous unincorporated villages (sixteen) and [[Hamlet (New York)|hamlets]]. Rockland County is designated as a [[List of Preserve America Communities|Preserve America Community]], and nearly a third of the county's area is parkland. The county has the largest [[American Jews|Jewish]] population per capita of any U.S. county, with 31.4%, or 90,000 residents, being Jewish.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rockland County|url=https://www.ny.gov/counties/rockland|website=New York State|accessdate=4 January 2019}}</ref> Rockland also ranked 31st on the list of highest-income counties by median [[household income in the United States]], with a median household income of $82,534 according to the 2010 census.\n\n==History==\n{{main|History of Rockland County, New York (1798\u20131900)}}\n[[File:Half Moon in Hudson.jpg|thumb|[[Henry Hudson]]'s ''Halve Maen'' (''Half Moon'') on the Hudson River]]\n[[File:SouthNyackNY CarsonMcCullersHouse.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Carson McCullers House]] in South Nyack]]\n[[File:DeWint House Tappan.JPG|thumb|[[DeWint House]] (circa 1700) is the oldest home in Rockland County.]]\n[[File:RocklandCountyCourthouse.jpg|thumb|Historic [[Rockland County Courthouse and Dutch Gardens|Rockland County Courthouse]] in New City]]\n\nThe area that would become Rockland County was originally inhabited by [[Algonquian languages|Algonquian]]-speaking Aboriginals, including [[Munsee]]s, or [[Lenni Lenape]].\n\nIn 1609, [[Henry Hudson]], thinking he had found the legendary \"[[Northwest Passage]]\", sailed on the ''Half Moon'' up the river that would one day bear his name and anchored near the area that is now [[Haverstraw, New York|Haverstraw]] before continuing to disillusionment north of [[Albany, New York|Albany]]. The [[Dutch people|Dutch]] were the first Europeans to settle in the area, around 1675.<ref name=NY>{{cite web|url=http://www.co.rockland.ny.us/Arts/history.htm|title=County of Rockland, New York :: Home |publisher=Co.rockland.ny.us|accessdate=3 February 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120311104721/http://www.co.rockland.ny.us/Arts/history.htm|archivedate=March 11, 2012}}</ref> These settlers, eager to escape \"city life\", moved from Manhattan to Rockland.  A number of unique Dutch-style red sandstone houses still stand, and many place names in the county reveal their Dutch origin. When the [[Duke of York]] (who became King [[James II of England]]) established the first twelve counties of New York in 1683, present-day Rockland County was part of [[Orange County, New York|Orange County]], known then as ''\"Orange County South of the Mountains\"''. [[Orangetown, New York|Orangetown]] was created at the same time under a royal grant, originally encompassing all of modern Rockland County. Around this time, as the English began to colonize [[Nyack, New York|Nyack]] and [[Tappan, New York|Tappan]], the Native Americans began to leave Rockland in search of undisturbed land further north.<ref name=NY/>\n\nThe natural barrier of the [[Ramapo Mountains]] and the size of the county made it difficult to carry out governmental activities. At one point there were twin governments, one on each side of the Ramapo Mountains. For this reason, Rockland split off from Orange in 1798 to form its own county. That same year the county seat was transferred from Tappan to New City, where a new courthouse was built.\n\nHaverstraw was separated from Orangetown in 1719 and became a town in 1788; it included the present-day [[Clarkstown, New York|Clarkstown]], [[Ramapo, New York|Ramapo]] and [[Stony Point, New York|Stony Point]]. Clarkstown and Ramapo became towns in 1791, followed by Stony Point in 1865.\n[[File:Lenapehoking.png|thumb|upright|The territory of the Lenape in present-day southern New York, New Jersey and eastern sections of Delaware and Pennsylvania]]\n\nDuring the [[American Revolution]], when control of the [[Hudson River]] was viewed by the [[Kingdom of Great Britain|British]] as strategic to dominating the American territories, Rockland saw [[battle|skirmishes]] at Haverstraw, Nyack and [[Piermont, New York|Piermont]], and significant military engagements at the [[Battle of Stony Point]], where General \"Mad\" [[Anthony Wayne]] earned his nickname. [[George Washington]] had headquarters for a time at John Suffern's tavern, the later site of the village of [[Suffern, New York|Suffern]]. British Major [[John Andr\u00e9]] met with American traitor [[Benedict Arnold]] near Stony Point to buy the plans for the [[fortification]]s at [[West Point, New York|West Point]]. Andr\u00e9 was captured with the plans in [[Tarrytown, New York|Tarrytown]] on his way back to the British lines; he was brought to Tappan for trial in the Tappan church, found guilty, hanged and buried nearby. Still another important chapter in the story of the Revolution was written on May 5, 1783, when General Washington received [[Guy Carleton, 1st Baron Dorchester|Sir Guy Carleton]] at the [[DeWint House]], where they discussed terms of a peace treaty. Two days later Washington visited Sir Guy aboard a British war vessel. On this day the King's Navy fired its first salute to the flag of the United States of America.\n\nIn the decades following the Revolution, Rockland became popular for its stone and bricks. These products, however, required quarrying in land that many later believed should be set aside as a preserve. Many unsuccessful efforts were made to turn much of the [[Hudson Highlands]] on the northern tip of the county into a forest preserve. However, [[Union Pacific Railroad]] president [[E. H. Harriman]] donated land as well as large sums of money for the purchase of properties in the area of [[Bear Mountain (Hudson Highlands)|Bear Mountain]]. [[Bear Mountain State Park|Bear Mountain]]/[[Harriman State Park (New York)|Harriman State Park]] became a reality in 1910 when Harriman's widow donated his lands to the state, and by 1914 it was estimated that more than a million people a year were coming to the park.  After [[World War I]], Rockland County became the most important sausage making hub in the state of [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref>[https://italianfoodctr.com/ Italian Food Center (accessed 18 July 2019)]</ref><ref>[https://patch.com/new-york/pearlriver/italian-fest-returns-blauvelt Italian Fest Returns to Blauvelt (accessed 18 July 2019)]</ref><ref>[http://www.hvmag.com/Hudson-Valley-Magazine/Calendar/index.php/name/9th-Annual-Blauvelt-Sons-of-Italy-Italian-Feast-Carnival/event/26440/ 9th Annual Blauvelt Sons of Italy Festival (accessed 18 July 2019)]</ref>\n\nRockland remained semi-rural until the 1950s when the [[Palisades Interstate Parkway]], [[Tappan Zee Bridge (1955\u20132017)|Tappan Zee Bridge]], and other major arteries were built. The idea of [[suburbia]] also helped transform the county. The county's population flourished, from 89,276 in 1950 to 265,475 in 1990.\n\n==Geography==\n[[Image:Ramapo Torne.jpg|thumb|300px|left|Ramapo Torne in [[Harriman State Park (New York)|Harriman State Park]], part of the [[Ramapo Mountains]]]]\nRockland County lies just north of the [[New Jersey]]-New York border, west of [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]] (across the [[Hudson River]]), and south of Orange County. Its east border is formed by the [[Tappan Zee]] portion of the Hudson River.<ref name=GM>[https://www.google.com/maps/place/Rockland+County,+NY/@41.2174135,-74.1017747,14z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x89c2c9caf11a7127:0x1f98163a4a0f684e!8m2!3d41.1489458!4d-73.9830029 Rockland County NY - Google Maps (accessed 10 July 2019)]</ref> The county's terrain ranges from 1,283' (391m) ASL on Rockhouse Mountain (northwest of Lake Welch)<ref>[https://www.peakbagger.com/peak.aspx?pid=7115 Rockhouse Mountain, New York (PeakBagger.com) Accessed 10 July 2019]</ref> to approaching sea level along the Hudson River. According to the US Census Bureau, the county has a total area of 199.34 sqmi (516&nbsp;km\u00b2), of which 173.55 sqmi (449.49&nbsp;km\u00b2) is land and 25.79 sqmi (66.80&nbsp;km\u00b2) (13%) is water.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/maps-data/data/docs/gazetteer/counties_list_36.txt|publisher=US Census Bureau|accessdate=January 7, 2015|date=August 22, 2012|title=2010 Census Gazetteer Files|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140519062322/http://www.census.gov/geo/maps-data/data/docs/gazetteer/counties_list_36.txt|archivedate=May 19, 2014}}</ref> It is the state's smallest county outside the five boroughs of New York City.\n\nApproximately 30% of Rockland County is devoted to parkland, belonging to either the five towns, incorporated villages, the state, or the county. These parks provide walking and hiking trails, ballfields, dog runs, historic sites, ponds, streams, salt marshes, and equestrian trails. Some popular state parks include [[Bear Mountain State Park]] on the northernmost tip of the county, [[Harriman State Park (New York)|Harriman State Park]] also along the county's northern boundary, and [[Nyack Beach State Park]] along the [[Hudson River]], with trails connecting to [[Rockland Lake State Park]]. The county hosts numerous public and private golf courses, with the towns of Orangetown, Ramapo, Stony Point, and Haverstraw all operating public golf courses within their towns. The [[Palisades Interstate Park Commission]] operates two golf courses in Rockland Lake State Park. Notable private courses in the county include [[Paramount Country Club]], Manhattan Woods Golf Course (designed by [[PGA Tour|PGA]] great [[Gary Player]]), and [[Rockland Country Club]] (Sparkill).\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Clarkstown NY Landscape.JPG|Overlooking Rockland County with NYC skyline in far background\nFile:Pine Meadow Lake.jpg|[[Pine Meadow Lake]] in [[Harriman State Park (New York)|Harriman State Park]]\nFile:Haverstraw NY Skyline.JPG|Haverstraw along the Hudson River\n</gallery>\n\n===Adjacent counties===\n{{div col}}\n* [[Orange County, New York|Orange County]] - northwest\n* [[Putnam County, New York|Putnam County]] - northeast\n* [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]] - east\n* [[Passaic County, New Jersey]] - west\n* [[Bergen County, New Jersey]] - south\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Lakes<ref name=GM/>===\n{{div col}}\n* Breakneck Pond\n* Congers Lake\n* Cranberry Pond\n* [[Lake DeForest]]\n* [[Lake Sebago]]\n* [[Lake Tappan]] (part)\n* Lake Wanoksink\n* [[Pine Meadow Lake]]\n* Potake Lake (part)\n* [[Rockland Lake (New York)|Rockland Lake]]\n* Second Reservoir\n* [[Sandyfield, New York|Lake Welch]]\n* [[Tappan Zee]] (along east border)\n* Third Reservoir\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1800= 6353\n|1810= 7758\n|1820= 8837\n|1830= 9388\n|1840= 11975\n|1850= 16962\n|1860= 22492\n|1870= 25213\n|1880= 27690\n|1890= 35162\n|1900= 38298\n|1910= 46873\n|1920= 45548\n|1930= 59599\n|1940= 74261\n|1950= 89276\n|1960= 136803\n|1970= 229903\n|1980= 259530\n|1990= 265475\n|2000= 286753\n|2010= 311687\n|estyear=2019\n|estimate=325789\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=US Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=US Decennial Census|publisher=US Census Bureau|accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref><br>1790-1960<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapserver.lib.virginia.edu|title=Historical Census Browser|publisher=University of Virginia Library|accessdate=January 7, 2015}}</ref> 1900-1990<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/ny190090.txt|title=Population of Counties by Decennial Census: 1900 to 1990|publisher=US Census Bureau|accessdate=January 7, 2015}}</ref><br>1990-2000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2000/briefs/phc-t4/tables/tab02.pdf|title=Census 2000 PHC-T-4. Ranking Tables for Counties: 1990 and 2000|publisher=US Census Bureau|accessdate=January 7, 2015}}</ref> 2010, 2019<ref name=QF/>\n}}\n\n===2000 census===\nAs of the [[2000 United States Census]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=US Census Bureau|accessdate=31 January 2008|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref> there were 286,753 people, 92,675 households, and 70,989 families in the county. The population density was 1,652/sqmi (638/km\u00b2). There were 94,973 housing units at an average density of 547/sqmi (211/km\u00b2). However, residents live closer together than the census numbers indicate, as 30% of the county is reserved as parkland. 9% of residents reported speaking Spanish at home, 5% [[Yiddish language|Yiddish]], 3% [[French-based creole languages|French-based creole]], 1.5% Italian, 1.3% [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]], 1.3% [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]], 1.2% French, and 1% Russian. Other languages spoken at home by at least 1000 people include [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]], [[Korean language|Korean]], Chinese, German, and [[Polish language|Polish]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 1em;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Rockland County Demographics\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"font-size: 90%\" | Racial demographics of Rockland according to 2016 US Census Bureau data:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/rocklandcountynewyork/PST045217 |title=Rockland County QuickFacts from the US Census Bureau|publisher=Quickfacts.census.gov|accessdate=17 February 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! Race\n! Percentage\n|-\n| [[White American|White]] ([[non-Hispanic Whites|Whites of non-Hispanic origin]]: 63.0%)\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 77.5%\n|-\n| [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Hispanics and Latinos]] (of any race)\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 17.6%\n|-\n| [[Black American|Black]]\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 13.3%\n|-\n| [[Asian American|Asian]]\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 6.5%\n|-\n| [[Multiracial American|Multiracial]]\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 2.0%\n|-\n| [[Native Americans in the United States|American Indian and Alaska Native persons]]\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 0.5%\n|-\n| [[Pacific Islander American|Native Hawaiian and Other Pacific Islander persons]]\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 0.1%\n|}\nThere were 92,675 households out of which 38% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 63% were married couples living together, 10% had a female householder with no husband present, and 23% were non-families. 19% of households were made up of individuals and 8% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 3 and the average family size was 3.5.\n\nThe county population contained 28% under the age of 18, 8% from 18 to 24, 28% from 25 to 44, 24.30% from 45 to 64, and 12% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 36 years. For every 100 women there were 95 men. For every 100 women age 18 and over, there were 91 men.\n\nThe median income for a household in the county was $68,000 and the median income for a family was $80,000. Males had a median income of $58,000 versus $39,000 for females. The per capita income for the county was $28,000. The mean, or average, income for a family in Rockland County is $73,500 according to the 2004 census. About 6% of families and 10% of the population were below the poverty line, including 14% of those under age 18 and 8% of those age 65 or over.\n{{clear}}\n\n==Education==\n[[File:United States Department of Education Blue Ribbon School Logo.jpg|thumb|100px|Blue ribbon School Logo]]\n[[File:Cherry Lane School.JPG|thumb|left|Cherry Lane Elementary School]]\nThe county is home to several [[Blue Ribbon Schools Program|Blue Ribbon School of Excellence Award]] winners, awarded by the [[U.S. Department of Education]]:\n{{div col}}\n* In 2000\u20132001, Liberty Elementary School in Valley Cottage (semi-finalists in 2004)\n* In 2007, Strawtown Elementary School in West Nyack\n* In 2008 & 2014, Franklin Avenue Elementary School in Pearl River\n* In 2009, George W. Miller Elementary School in Nanuet\n* In 2011, Pearl River Middle School in Pearl River\n* In 2013, Cherry Lane Elementary School in Suffern\n* In 2016, Nanuet Senior High School In Nanuet\n* In 2018, Clarkstown High School South\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Colleges and Universities===\nThe county is home to several colleges and universities. ''For more information please visit [[List of colleges and universities in New York (state)]]''\n* [[State University of New York|SUNY]]:\n** [[Rockland Community College]] - [[Suffern, NY]]\n* [[Private University]]:\n** [[Dominican College (New York)|Dominican College]] (Dominican College of Blauvelt) - [[Orangeburg, NY]]\n** [[Long Island University]] extension site at [[Rockland Community College]] - [[Suffern, NY]]\n** [[Columbia University]]'s [[Lamont\u2013Doherty Earth Observatory]]\n** [[Nyack College]] - [[Nyack, NY]]\n** Rabbinical College Beth Shraga - [[Monsey, NY]]\n** [[St. Thomas Aquinas College]] - [[Sparkill, New York|Sparkill, NY]]\n** Yeshiva D'Monsey Rabbinical College - [[Monsey, NY]]\n** Yeshivath Viznitz - [[Kaser, New York|Kaser, NY]] ([[Monsey, NY]]}\n\n===High schools===\n{{further|List of high schools in New York#Rockland County}}\n\n===School districts===\n* [[Clarkstown Central School District]]\n** In 2015 [[U.S. News & World Report]] ranked Clarkstown North Senior High School with a Silver award as 135th Best High School in New York State and at 1,329 nationally.<ref>\n[https://www.usnews.com/education/best-high-schools/new-york/districts/clarkstown-central-school-district/clarkstown-north-senior-high-school-13901 2015 Academic Indicators]</ref>\n** In 2017 U.S. News & World Report ranked Clarkstown South Senior High School with a Silver award as 116th Best High School in New York State and at 1,219 nationally.\n** In 2017 U.S. News & World Report ranked Clarkstown North Senior High School with a Silver award as 117th Best High School in New York State and at 1,224 nationally.\n** In 2018, ranked 78 Best School Districts in Clarkstown by [[Niche (company)|Niche's]].\n* [[East Ramapo Central School District]]\n** In 2019, U.S. News & World Report ranked Ramapo High School 765th in New York State and 10,493th in the US.\n** In 2019, U.S. News & World Report ranked Spring Valley High School 820th in New York State and 11,474th in the US.\n* [http://www.nanuetsd.org/ Nanuet Union Free School District]\n** In 2018, ranked 89 Best School Districts in Nanuet by Niche.\n** In 2018, National School Boards Association 2018 Magna Award was awarded to the Nanuet Public Schools in recognition of the Outdoor Education Center.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nsba.org/newsroom/american-school-board-journal/asbj-april-2018/breaking-down-barriers/outdoor-education|title=Outdoor Education Center - National School Boards Association|website=www.nsba.org}}</ref>\n* [[North Rockland Central School District]]\n** In 2017 U.S. News & World Report ranked North Rockland Senior High School with a Bronze award as New York's 219th Best High School.\n** In 2018, ranked 179 2018 Best School Districts in North Rockland by Niche.\n* [[Nyack Public Schools]]\n** In 2018, ranked 68 Best School Districts in Nyack by Niche.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140507063146/http://www.pearlriver.org/education/district/district.php?sectionid=1 Pearl River School District]\n** In 2017 U.S. News & World Report ranked Pearl River High School with a Silver award as 76th Best High School in New York State and at 727 nationally.\n** In 2018, ranked 214 Best School Districts in Pearl River by Niche.\n* [[Ramapo Central School District|Suffern Central School District]]\n** Suffern Senior High School was ranked #53 (out of 938 public high schools) on Niche's 2016 Best Public High Schools in New York, and #343 (out of 16,464 public high schools) in the country.\n** In 2017 U.S. News & World Report ranked Suffern Senior High School with a Silver award as 111th Best High School in New York State and #1179 nationally.\n** In 2018, ranked 26 Best School Districts in Suffern by Niche\n* [http://www.socsd.org/ South Orangetown Central School District]\n** In 2017 U.S. News & World Report ranked Tappan Zee High School with a Silver award as 66th Best High School in New York State and #643 nationally.\n** In 2018, ranked 71 Best School Districts in Orangetown by Niche.\n\n==Transportation==\n[[Image:TappanZeeBridgeFromBelow.JPG|thumb|The [[Tappan Zee Bridge (1955\u20132017)|Tappan Zee Bridge]] connected Rockland and Westchester counties across the Hudson River. It was [[Tappan Zee Bridge (2017\u2013present)|replaced]] in 2017.]] The [[Tappan Zee Bridge (2017\u2013present)|Tappan Zee Bridge]] connects [[South Nyack, New York|South Nyack]] in Rockland County and [[Tarrytown, New York|Tarrytown]] in [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]] across the [[Hudson River]] in the [[Lower Hudson Valley]] of [[New York State]]. The [[Tappan Zee Bridge (1955\u20132017)|old bridge]] was replaced with a new span in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lohud.com/article/20121217/NEWS03/312170096/It-s-official-State-picks-builder-new-Tappan-Zee-Bridge|title=It's official: State picks builder for new Tappan Zee Bridge|author=Khurram Saeed and Theresa Juva-Brown|publisher=Copyright \u00a9 2012 www.lohud.com. All rights reserved|date=17 December 2012|accessdate=9 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Major highways===\n{{See also|County routes in New York}}\nThe county is served by several major highways, including [[Interstate 87 (New York)|Interstate 87]]/[[Interstate 287|287]] (the [[New York Thruway]]), opening from [[Suffern, New York|Suffern]] to [[Yonkers, New York|Yonkers]] in 1955. The [[Tappan Zee Bridge (1955\u20132017)|Tappan Zee Bridge]] opened the same year, connecting Rockland and Westchester, allowing Rockland County's population to grow rapidly. The [[Palisades Interstate Parkway]], a project of master planner [[Robert Moses]] and built between 1947 and 1958, connects the county directly to the [[George Washington Bridge]] due south. The [[Garden State Parkway]] opened in 1955, connecting [[New Jersey]] to I-87/287.\n{{div col}}\n* {{jct|state=NY|I|87}}\n* {{jct|state=NY|I|287}}\n* {{jct|state=NY|US|6}}\n* {{jct|state=NY|US|9W}}\n* {{jct|state=NY|US|202}}\n* {{jct|state=NY|Parkway|Garden State}}\n* {{jct|state=NY|Parkway|Palisades}}\n* {{jct|state=NY|NY|17}}\n* {{jct|state=NY|NY|45}}\n* {{jct|state=NY|NY|59}}\n* {{jct|state=NY|NY|210}}\n* {{jct|state=NY|NY|303}}\n* {{jct|state=NY|NY|304}}\n* {{jct|state=NY|NY|340}}\n{{div col end}}\n[[File:Mario Cuomo Bridge Overhead.jpg|thumb|220x220px|Governor Mario Cuomo Bridge]]\nFor further information\n* [[List of county routes in Rockland County, New York]]\n* [[List of county routes in Rockland County, New York (1\u201338)]]\n* [[List of county routes in Rockland County, New York (41\u201375)]]\n* [[List of county routes in Rockland County, New York (76\u2013118A)]]\n\n===Bus===\n[[File:TOR Bus.JPG|thumb|Hybrid electric bus operated by Transport of Rockland]]\nThe [[Transport of Rockland]] operates several local bus routes throughout the county, as well as the express bus [[Hudson Link]] routes to city centers and train stations in Tarrytown and [[White Plains, New York|White Plains]] in Westchester County. TOR provides connections to other neighborhood bus operations&nbsp;\u2013  Minitrans<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.town.clarkstown.ny.us/html/mini_trans.html|title=Minitrans|publisher=Town.clarkstown.ny.us|accessdate=3 February 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160515205056/http://www.town.clarkstown.ny.us/html/mini_trans.html|archivedate=May 15, 2016}}</ref> and connections to private commuter lines, [[Rockland Coaches]] and [[Short Line (bus company)|Short Line]] providing service to [[northern New Jersey]] and New York City.\n[[File:RocklandBusMap.pdf|thumb|Transportation map]]\n\n===Railroad===\n[[NJ Transit]]/[[Metro-North Railroad]] operates the [[Port Jervis Line]], which stops at the [[Suffern (NJT station)|Suffern Railroad Station]] and [[Sloatsburg (Metro-North station)|Sloatsburg Station]], and the [[Pascack Valley Line]], whose stops include [[Pearl River (Metro-North station)|Pearl River]], [[Nanuet (Metro-North station)|Nanuet]], and [[Spring Valley (Metro-North station)|Spring Valley]]. in their respective hamlets and village of the same name. Connections on this line are available at [[Secaucus, New Jersey|Secaucus]] for service to [[Pennsylvania Station (New York City)|Penn Station]] in [[Midtown Manhattan]] and service to the [[Meadowlands Sports Complex]] in [[East Rutherford, New Jersey]]. The southern terminus of both lines is [[Hoboken Terminal]] in New Jersey, where connections can be made to several [[NJ Transit Bus Operations|NJ Transit bus lines]], ferries, and [[Port Authority Trans-Hudson|PATH trains]] to New York City.\n\nUntil 1958, Rockland County's eastern side was served by the [[New York Central Railroad]]'s passenger service on the [[West Shore Railroad]] from [[Weehawken, New Jersey]], opposite Midtown Manhattan up through Tappan, west Nyack, Congers, Haverstraw, on to the West Hudson shore cities of Newburgh, Kingston and Albany. The service ran to West Haverstraw, in the north of the until 1959.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nyc.railfan.net/ws-jk.html|title=Comments On The West Shore from James Knecht|website=Nyc.railfan.net|accessdate=19 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=New York Central Railroad, Table 50|journal=Official Guide of the Railways |publisher=National Railway Publication Company |volume=92 |issue=7 |date=December 1959}}</ref> The [[Erie Railroad]] ran train service on the [[Northern Branch]] through the southeastern corner of the county to Nyack up to 1966.<ref>{{Citation| title=COMMUTERS LOSE BID TO KEEP ERIE TRAINS | newspaper=The New York Times | date=October 3, 1966 | page=58 | accessdate=June 7, 2010 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1966/10/03/archives/commuters-lose-bid-to-keep-erie-trains.html}}</ref>\n\n===Ferry===\n[[NY Waterway]] operates a [[Haverstraw\u2013Ossining Ferry|ferry]] service between [[Haverstraw, New York|Haverstraw]] and [[Ossining (village), New York|Ossining]] in Westchester County for the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]. Commuters take the Transport of Rockland's Ferry Express route to the Haverstraw ferry terminal for service to [[Metro-North Railroad|Metro-North's]] [[Hudson Line (Metro-North)|Hudson Line]] service to [[Grand Central Terminal]]. Ferry service is typically suspended in the colder months when the Hudson River freezes over, and commuters must take shuttle buses across the [[Tappan Zee Bridge (2017\u2013present)|Tappan Zee Bridge]].\n\n===Airports===\nNearby airports include:\n* New York: [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]], [[LaGuardia Airport]], [[Westchester County Airport]], and [[Stewart International Airport]]\n* New Jersey: [[Newark Liberty International Airport]], [[Teterboro Airport]]\n\n==Law, government and politics==\n===United States House of Representatives===\nAll of Rockland County falls within the [[New York's 17th congressional district|17th Congressional District]], along with central and western Westchester County. The district is represented by Congresswoman [[Nita Lowey|Nita M. Lowey]] (as of 2019).\n\n===New York State politicians===\nThe county of Rockland is represented in the [[New York State Senate]] by David Carlucci (D) of the 38th district and James Skoufis (D) of the 39th district (as of 2019).<ref>[http://www.nysenate.gov/district/38 38th District (accessed 10 July 2019)]</ref><ref>[http://www.nysenate.gov/district/39 39th District (accessed 10 July 2019)]</ref>\n\n{| style=\"float:left;\"  border=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"4\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\"  style=\"text-align:center; background:#0047ab; color:#fff;\"|Rockland County Assemblymen & Women\n|-\n!  style=\"background:red; text-align:center; color:#fff;\"| <center>Name</center>\n!  style=\"background:red; text-align:center; color:#fff;\"| <center> [[New York State Assembly|NYS Assembly]] </center>\n!  style=\"background:red; text-align:center; color:#fff;\"| <center>Party</center>\n|-\n|- {{party shading/Democratic}}\n| [[Kenneth Zebrowski, Jr.]] || <center>96th District</center> || <center>Democrat</center>\n|-\n|- {{party shading/Democratic}}\n| [[Ellen Jaffee|Ellen C. Jaffee]] || <center>97th District</center> || <center>Democrat</center>\n|}\n{{clear}}\n\n===County politicians===\nRockland County government is led by County Executive. Republican Ed Day was first elected in 2013 and re-elected in 2017. The previous county executive was Republican C. Scott Vanderhoef, who was re-elected in 2009 to his fifth four-year term. Day is the third county executive in Rockland history, with Vanderhoef having defeated the incumbent, John T. Grant (D), in 1993. Prior to 1985, Rockland County did not have a county executive. County Executive Day was sworn in for his second term on January 1, 2018.\n\nThe county is divided into 17 single-member districts.<ref>[http://rocklandgov.com/elected-officials/ Elected Officials]</ref> The Chairman of the Legislature is Alden H. Wolfe. In the November 2019 election the republicans gained one seat moving the democrats majority from 10\u20137 to 9\u20138. The current legislators are - a